Introduction

We have a dataset of nearly 130,000 different wines with their ratings, price, tasters, country of origin, variety and much more. That is a lot of wine to look at so we are going to narrow it down to wines from one of my favorite places Portugal.

## [1] 5691   14

Using dim(df) we can see that there are 5691 different wines, and 92 varieties. If we put all 92 into a bar graph its a little messy, so we are going to ignore the varieties that have a less than 20 wines in them. Now lets take a look at the different varieties of wine Portugal has to offer.

Theres a lot of wines there. I could just show you a table if I used kable(WP), but whats the fun in that, and itd be a lot of scrolling. With DT::datable(WP) you can search anything in the table.

If you search Port you will see there are 607 varieties of Port made in Portugal. We are going to focus on this specific variety of wine.

Port Wine

Price of Port by points

We see that Ports that received points from 80 to 95 in general have a similar price range, but when a port receives 95 plus points, then the price really jumps.

Count of wineries making Port in Portugal

If we look at the Port by the winery we can tell there are 97 different wineries, by using wine <- filter(wine, variety == 'Port') %>% group_by(winery) %>% summarise(count = n())

Now it be great to be able to taste wines from all these different places, but lets narrow the Ports down to a few you can commonly purchase in the United States.

As you can see Taylor Flagate and Kopke have the most Ports in this dataset. Now Lets move away from the data and go look where these Ports come from.
